At the moment there's no way this can be done using the graphic user interface, but can easily be done from the command line.
You can do this by using the option --exclude-from [text file of Directories and/or files to exclude]. Here's an example of how I use it:

sudo aptik --backup-all --basepath /media/roy/'Linux Backups'/Aptik --scripted --exclude-from .skipped_files

Aptik will read the text file and skip those files in your home folder when the --exclude-from [text file] is used.

In my example above it reads the .skipped_files file which contains:

Music
Pictures
Dropbox
.Dropbox

Now when I use aptik and use the option --exclude-from .skipped_files it will skip over those folders in my Home directory and the archive it creates is much smaller that if I hadn't used it.

To Backup to Kdrive Infomaniak with APTIK:
To back up your system using Aptik to a network drive (such as an Infomaniak kDrive mounted via WebDAV), 


you must first ensure the network drive is mounted as a local directory on your Linux system, as Aptik primarily backs up to local paths.

1. Mount the Network Drive You need to mount your network storage (e.g., kDrive, NAS, or SMB share) to a specific folder on your computer.

    For kDrive (WebDAV): You can use the official kDrive desktop app to sync a folder, or mount it via command line using davfs2. If using the desktop app, simply note the local path where kDrive syncs (e.g., ~/kDrive). If mounting manually, install davfs2, add your credentials to /etc/davfs2/secrets, and mount the WebDAV URL (e.g., https://<ID>.connect.kdrive.infomaniak.com) to a folder like /mnt/kdrive.
    For standard Network Shares (SMB/NFS): Use your file manager or mount commands to attach the share to a local directory (e.g., /mnt/backup-drive).

2. Configure Aptik to Use the Mounted Path Once the drive is mounted and visible as a folder in your file system:

    Open your terminal.
    Run Aptik with the --store option pointing to a folder on your mounted drive.

    bash
    sudo aptik --store=/path/to/mounted/drive/aptik-backup

    (Replace /path/to/mounted/drive/ with the actual path, e.g., /mnt/kdrive/ or ~/kDrive/).
    Aptik will now save your applications, settings, and PPA lists directly to that network location.

Important Considerations:

    Connection Stability: Ensure the network drive is mounted before running Aptik. If the connection drops during the backup, the process may fail or result in incomplete data.
    Permissions: Your user account must have write permissions to the mounted folder.
    Restoration: To restore, the drive must be mounted at the same path (or you must specify the new path using --restore=/path/to/...).

For detailed steps on mounting Infomaniak kDrive via WebDAV on Linux, you can refer to the official guide: Se connecter à kDrive par WebDAV.
